Looking at the test `testIntersectionNotIntersecting` and the implementation of the `intersection` method in SubLine.java, I can see the issue. The test expects that when two sub-lines don't intersect (in this case, they are skew lines - lines that don't intersect and are not parallel), the method should return `null`. However, the current implementation doesn't handle the case where the underlying infinite lines don't intersect.

Looking at the `intersection` method:

```java
public Vector3D intersection(final SubLine subLine, final boolean includeEndPoints) {

    // compute the intersection on infinite line
    Vector3D v1D = line.intersection(subLine.line);

    // check location of point with respect to first sub-line
    Location loc1 = remainingRegion.checkPoint(line.toSubSpace(v1D));

    // check location of point with respect to second sub-line
    Location loc2 = subLine.remainingRegion.checkPoint(subLine.line.toSubSpace(v1D));

    if (includeEndPoints) {
        return ((loc1 != Location.OUTSIDE) && (loc2 != Location.OUTSIDE)) ? v1D : null;
    } else {
        return ((loc1 == Location.INSIDE) && (loc2 == Location.INSIDE)) ? v1D : null;
    }

}
```

The problem is that the method calls `line.intersection(subLine.line)` without checking if this returns `null`. In 3D space, two lines may not have an intersection point (they could be skew lines). If the underlying `Line.intersection` method returns `null`, then the subsequent code will throw a `NullPointerException` when trying to use `v1D`.

Let me check the Line class to understand how intersection works:

